        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> > At line 56 in src/nvim/msgpack_rpc/server.c, I added this.\n> > ```\n> > if (rv == UV_EADDRINUSE){\n> >       unlink(listen_addr);\n> >   }\n> > ```\n> > \n> > \n> >     \n> >       \n> >     \n> > \n> >       \n> >     \n> > \n> >     \n> >   \n> > It correctly removes the file on the second try. According to what was written above, this was one of the desired solutions ( connect and remove upon failure ). If the fix is ok, I can submit a PR.\n> \n> This doesn't make sense. Nvim should not remove a socket file it didn't create.\n\nI didn't find any way to deduce if Nvim created it or not. You can do some bookkeeping when creating the socket, but that's really ugly. An alternative I thought of is this\n\n```\n  int fd = socket(AF_UNIX, SOCK_STREAM, 0);\n  if (fd >= 0) {\n    struct sockaddr_un sa = {0};\n    sa.sun_family = AF_UNIX;\n      xstrlcpy(sa.sun_path, listen_addr, sizeof(sa.sun_path));\n\n    int ret = connect(fd, (struct sockaddr *)&sa, sizeof(sa));\n    close(fd);\n    if (ret < 0 && errno == ECONNREFUSED) {\n      /*ECONNREFUSED\n              A connect() on a stream socket found no one listening on\n              the remote address.*/\n\n      WLOG(\"Removing stale socket %s\", listen_addr);\n      unlink(listen_addr);\n    } else if (ret == 0) {\n        WLOG(\"Socket %s already in use by another process\", listen_addr);\n    } else {\n        WLOG(\"Socket %s unverifiable (errno=%d)\", listen_addr, errno);\n    }\n  }\n```\n\nEDIT: This can still technically remove a socket Neovim did not create, but ECONNREFUSED can guarantee that it isn't being used.",
